%S A396869 4,3,0,4,3,7,0,8,3,0,4,12,11,0,8,16,3,7,4,20,3,19,0,16,11,19,0,12,28,
%T A396869 3,27,0,8,32,27,4,12,28,36,11,0,16,24,28,40,19,27,20,28,3,27,43,0,16,
%U A396869 40,48,35,43,4,12,3,51,8,16,32,56,3,11,43,0,4,28,52,60,19,35,43,0
%N A396869 a(n) = 4*q - floor(2*sqrt(q))^2, where q = A246655(n).
%C A396869 Sequences lists negated discriminants of the finite fields, defined in the thesis of Zaitsev and the Alekseenko et al paper to study algebraic curves over finite fields.
%C A396869 Terms are congruent to 0 or 3 modulo 4. Each number congruent to 7 modulo 8 can only occur finitely many times: if x^2 + d = 4*p^n for prime p and d == 7 (mod 8), then modulo 8 we have p = 2, and the equation x^2 + d = 4*2^n can be partitioned into three elliptic curves X^2 + X + (d+1)/4 = Y^3, X^2 + X + (d+1)/4 = 2*Y^3, and X^2 + X + (d+1)/4 = 4*Y^3, each having only finitely many integer solutions.
%C A396869 Conjecturally, for every d == 0, 3, 4 (mod 8), there are only finitely many solutions (x,p,n) to x^2 + d = 4*p^n, with p >= 3 prime, n >= 3 odd. See the Muriefah et al link for the cases of small values d == 0 (mod 4), and the Luca et al link for the cases of small values d == 3 (mod 4). (Here only the case p not dividing d is treated in the Luca et al link, but the case p dividing d can be solved using elliptic curves, similar to the previous paragraph). In particular, the indices n of d <= 20 are as follows, where q = A246655(n):
%C A396869   - d = 0: q in A246655^2;
%C A396869   - d = 3: q in A002383 U {343};
%C A396869   - d = 4: q in A002496;
%C A396869   - d = 7: only q = 8, 32, 8192;
%C A396869   - d = 8: q in (A056899 \ {2,3}) U {27};
%C A396869   - d = 11: q in (A027753 \ {3,5}) U {243};
%C A396869   - d = 12: q in A049423 \ {3,7};
%C A396869   - d = 15: no solutions exist;
%C A396869   - d = 16: q in (A005473 \ {5,13}) U {125};
%C A396869   - d = 19: q in (A027755 \ {5,7,11,17}) U {78125};
%C A396869   - d = 20: q in A056905 \ {5}.
%H A396869 Jianing Song, <a href="/A396869/b396869.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A396869 E. Alekseenko, S. Aleshnikov, N. Markin and A. Zaytsev, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/0902.1901">Optimal Curves of Genus 3 over Finite Fields with Discriminant -19</a>, arXiv:0902.1901 [math.AG], 2009-2011. See Definition 1.1.
%H A396869 Florian Luca, Szabolcs Tengely, and Alain Togbé, <a href="https://www.labmath.uqam.ca/~annales/volumes/33-2/PDF/171-184.pdf">On the Diophantine equation x^2 + C = 4y^n</a>. See Theorem 1.1.
%H A396869 Fadwa S. Abu Muriefah and Yann Bugeanud, <a href="https://irma.math.unistra.fr/~bugeaud/travaux/EqAbu1.pdf">The Diophantine equation x^2 + c = y^n: a brief overview</a>.
%H A396869 A.I. Zaitsev, <a href="https://hdl.handle.net/11245/1.279638">Optimality properties of curves over finite fields</a>, University of Armsterdam. See Section 3.1.
%t A396869 Map[4*# - Floor[2*Sqrt[#]]^2 &, Select[Range[500], PrimePowerQ]] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Jun 09 2026 *)
%o A396869 (PARI) A396869_up_to_N(q) = my(v, r); v = select(x->isprimepower(x), vector(q, i, i)); apply(x->sqrtint(4*x, &r); r, v)
%Y A396869 Cf. A246655, A396895 (for finite fields of prime order).
%Y A396869 Cf. A002383, A002496, A056899, A027753, A049423, A005473, A027755, A056905.
%Y A396869 Cf. discriminants of finite fields whose order is an odd power of p: A201125 (p=2), A396870 (p=3), A396871 (p=5), A396872 (p=7).
